# Class: :BWMD_0010665 (Quenching)

AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label :BWMD_0010665 "Quenching"@en)
AnnotationAssertion(skos:definition :BWMD_0010665 "Material is heated up to the suitable temperature and then quenched in water or oil to harden to full hardness according to the kind of steels.

Material is heated to the suitable temperature for hardening, then cooled rapidly by immersing the hot part is water, oil or another suitable liquid to transform the material to a fully hardened structure. Parts which are quenched usually must be aged, tempered or stress relieved to achieve the proper toughness, final hardness and dimensional stability.

Alloys may be air cooled, or cooled by quenching in oil, water, or another liquid, depending upon the amount of alloying elements in the material and final mechanical properties to be achieved. Hardened materials are tempered to improve their dimensional stability and toughness."@en)
SubClassOf(:BWMD_0010665 :BWMD_0010332)

# Class: :BWMD_0010666 (Quenching Duration)

AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:comment :BWMD_0010666 "Aligned to PMDco by Excel mapping: subClassOf 'process attribute'; classification='process attribute'; confidence='high'.")
AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label :BWMD_0010666 "Quenching Duration"@en)
AnnotationAssertion(owl:versionInfo :BWMD_0010666 "This class was added by Elena Garcia Trelles (Fraunhofer IWM)")
AnnotationAssertion(skos:definition :BWMD_0010666 "Duration of the quenching step indicating the amount of time in which the heat treated object is submerged in the quenching medium in order to be quickly cooled down until the heat treated object reaches the temperature of the quenching medium."@en)
SubClassOf(:BWMD_0010666 :BWMD_0010335)

